C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu wrote:
>    Anyone can design a cipher with a long key.  The question, still un-
> answered, is "does IDEA's security merit a 128-bit key?"  The same
> questions can be asked of Skipjack's 80-bit key, since nobody will
> *really* know if Skipjack is any stronger than DES, or even as strong
> as DES, unless there's public review of the algorithm.  (A similar
> argument can be applied to 160-bit or 256-bit hash functions--are
> collisions *really* going to require on the order of 2**80 or 2**128
> operations to find?)

And there's the additional problem of getting people to pick
random-enough passwords to merit the number of bits in the key.
Triple IDEA with 384 bits of key wouldn't do you much good if you used
the name of your pet as your password.

Well, unless you pick the name of your pet very carefully...
